article.description:
The Los Angeles Clippers don't have much
success holding onto fourth-quarter leads. Playing Memphis gave
them a good chance to practice.
article.headline: Maggette gets hot late to lift Los Angeles past Memphis
article.linkText: Clippers prove they can hold a fourth-quarter lead
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers don't have much success holding onto fourth-quarter leads. Playing Memphis gave them a good chance to practice. Corey Maggette scored six of his 18 points in the final 3:19 as the Clippers snapped a four-game losing streak with a 102-100 victory Sunday night. The Clippers came in having lost 20 games that they led after three quarters, but they held on to win this one after nearly letting a seven-point lead slip away late. ''I'm as happy as anybody could be,'' said interim coach Dennis Johnson, who is 4-11 since replacing Alvin Gentry on March 3. ''We held up down the stretch against matters that normally knock us off the pedestal. I'm glad the guys pulled through. These are games we need to win.'' In the first game of a two-night stand in Staples Center, the Grizzlies squandered their best chance to record the first winning month in the franchise's eight-year history. They are 8-7 in March with one game left -- against the Lakers, who are 17-0 at home against the Grizzlies. Rookie Chris Wilcox added 15 points for the Clippers, who won for only the sixth time in 28 games. Mike Miller scored 29 points for the Grizzlies, who have lost five in a row to the Clippers in Los Angeles. It was Memphis' third consecutive defeat overall and fifth in six games after winning seven of their previous eight. ''Mike's a great player. He's playing out there hurt, too, and he doesn't get any credit for it,'' teammate Lorenzen Wright said. ''His back is bothering him, and he's squinting and grinding every time he takes a shot.'' Pau Gasol added 19 points and 12 rebounds for Memphis. Maggette, who scored a career-high 34 points against the Grizzlies in a 116-111 defeat Jan. 3 in Memphis, sank a pair of free throws and added a 17-footer to give Los Angeles a 99-92 cushion with 1:15 to play. Miller made his fifth 3-pointer in as many tries to cut the deficit to 99-98 with 50 seconds left, but he missed another shot from behind the arc, and Marko Jaric rebounded and was fouled. ''We executed what we wanted to run,'' Grizzlies coach Hubie Brown said. ''That was a wide-open shot by a guy who had 29 points. You can't get a better shot than that. The ball went right in the basket and came out. When it came down to the last two shots that we needed, we got two good shots.'' Jaric made one of two free throws with one second left, giving the Grizzlies one more chance. But Wesley Person missed a 19-footer from the right baseline after getting an inbounds pass from Jason Williams. Los Angeles won despite having its starting front line of Lamar Odom, Cherokee Parks and Sean Rooks outscored 61-26 by Miller, Gasol and Wright. ''Right now, trying to win a game is the only challenge,'' Odom said. ''At times tonight I was frustrated, and I guess my body language showed it. We just let them play with us. They didn't want to play in the first half, and we let them get back in the game.'' The Grizzlies, who shot a season-worst 32.1 percent from the field in a defeat Friday at Seattle, didn't take their first lead until 32 seconds into the third when Jason Williams sank a free throw after Odom got a technical foul. Game notes
Injured Grizzlies rookie Chris Owens, whose senior year at Texas ended after 11 games because of a knee injury, was on the court an hour and 47 minutes before tipoff, when the Longhorns clinched their first Final Four berth in 56 years. ''I knew it was coming. I always had faith in them,'' Owens said. ''Everybody gave them a hard time about being a No. 1 seed, but they proved why they are -- and now they're going to prove why they're the best team in the country.'' ... Elton Brand should know by Monday when -- or if -- he will be able to return to the court before the season ends. He has missed 18 games because of a stress fracture in his lower left leg. ... Quentin Richardson, who missed the previous three games because of a bruised tendon in his left knee, had seven points in 17 minutes.
